ly to our understanding of gender, slave status, and the matrilineal principle of descent in the Ancient Near East.  afunded by Knowledge Unlatched  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gender Studies.2bisacsh1 aKriger, Akiva, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMeacham, Tirzah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb2 aKnowledge Unlatchedefunder.4fnd4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/fnd08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAcademic Studies Press Backlist eBook-Package 2008-2015z978311068814608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertReligious Studies ASPz978311071683240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781644693292zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de GruyterzOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781644693292zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781644693292/original  a978-3-11-068814-6 Academic Studies Press Backlist eBook-Package 2008-2015c2008d2015  a978-3-11-071683-2 Religious Studies ASP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA